    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:cc0ed748c34c660b85d34ac594e72724",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C1",
      "statement": "*The repository of 152 initiatives across 44 countries is an explicitly partial, English-skewed snapshot (Europe/North America over-represented; coastal/aquatic hubs notably absent), surfaced through three filtering criteria.* This is a `tooling-map`-adjacent artifact: an indexed field survey with documented coverage gaps. The methodological honesty about skew is itself a precedent for how this repo should caveat its own mapping outputs.",
      "schema:confidence": "high",
      "anchor": "§Project Repository: At a Glance · orn:biohubs.whitepaper:repository",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
      "about": [
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.layer",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.story-of-place",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.bioregion",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.watershed",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.stewardship",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.practitioner",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.field",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.tooling-map"
      ],
      "isPartOf": "bioregional-mapping.connection.biohubs-regional-resilience-mapping"
    },
    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:0896e2ea69c486674e8e570e8726493b",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C2",
      "statement": "*Site footprint and area of influence are distinct mapping quantities: across 59 sized projects the median site is ~44 ha (mean 285 ha), and 12 hubs that record a stewardship/influence area report it averaging 21× (up to 150×+) the owned site — e.g. Sinal do Vale operates a 173-ha site across a 200,000-ha watershed.* The site-vs-reach gap is a load-bearing mapping distinction at the `watershed`/`bioregion` scale: the polygon a hub owns is not the polygon it stewards.",
      "schema:confidence": "high",
      "anchor": "§Sites & Their Reach",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
      "about": [
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.layer",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.story-of-place",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.bioregion",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.watershed",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.stewardship",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.practitioner",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.field",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.tooling-map"
      ],
      "isPartOf": "bioregional-mapping.connection.biohubs-regional-resilience-mapping"
    },
    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:81d0e1f27d5b234298aa0919a5eabb2b",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C3",
      "statement": "*The seven \"ingredients\" (Land & Ecology; Food & Material Flows; Knowledge & Learning; Culture & Social Fabric; Governance & Stewardship; Finance & Enterprise; Human Health & Inner Development) compose a multi-domain reading of a place.* This is a near-parallel to this repo's six-layer rubric (relational/cultural/ecological/economic/governance/geospatial) — an external corroboration that mapping a hub/region means holding multiple domains as distinct `layer`s rather than a single map.",
      "schema:confidence": "high",
      "anchor": "§BioHub Design Framework · §Ingredients",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
      "about": [
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.layer",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.story-of-place",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.bioregion",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.watershed",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.stewardship",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.practitioner",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.field",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.tooling-map"
      ],
      "isPartOf": "bioregional-mapping.connection.biohubs-regional-resilience-mapping"
    },
    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:3ee9f3259837e9debd788c861b46285a",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C4",
      "statement": "*The Regenesis Group's \"Story of Place\" — reading a place as the sum of its ecological, cultural, and economic energies, uncovering its \"vocation\" before intervening — is presented as the foundational pre-mapping assessment.* This directly affirms `story-of-place` as both method and artifact in this repo: deep regional assessment precedes and grounds any focal intervention.",
      "schema:confidence": "high",
      "anchor": "§Finding Your Focal Point",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
      "about": [
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.layer",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.story-of-place",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.bioregion",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.watershed",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.stewardship",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.practitioner",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.field",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.tooling-map"
      ],
      "isPartOf": "bioregional-mapping.connection.biohubs-regional-resilience-mapping"
    },
    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:ae07d3cf008bd6e6cdebf92843c2db8e",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C5",
      "statement": "*A recurring success pattern is long-horizon `stewardship` and deep rootedness in place — a ~five-year threshold (echoed by Bill Reed of Regenesis) before results become visible enough to attract consistent support.* For mapping `practitioner`s this sets a realistic time-base: mapping is the start of a multi-year stewardship rhythm, not a one-time deliverable — consistent with this repo's framing of mapping as ongoing `field` practice.",
      "schema:confidence": "medium",
      "anchor": "§Recurring Patterns of Success",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
      "about": [
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.layer",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.story-of-place",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.bioregion",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.watershed",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.stewardship",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.practitioner",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.field",
        "bioregional-mapping.concept.tooling-map"
      ],
      "isPartOf": "bioregional-mapping.connection.biohubs-regional-resilience-mapping"
    },
    {
      "@id": "orn:koi-net.claim:fc64e7bdfc98d5086462385100077b3c",
      "@type": "Claim",
      "identifier": "C6",
      "statement": "*Under a proximity classification, 47% of hubs are peri-urban, 41% rural/remote, 12% urban — challenging the field's default rural orientation.* A geospatial-`layer` finding worth carrying into this repo's site-classification scheme: proximity/commute-access is a distinct axis from population density or land character.",
      "schema:confidence": "medium",
      "anchor": "§The Peri-Urban Sweet Spot",
      "claimType": "governance",
      "attributedTo": "org:bioregional-mapping-learning-field",
